  "answer": "Across the smriti corpus, 'āśrama' denotes a life-stage or order of life. The classical four āśramas are: (1) brahmacāri (celibate student), (2) gṛhastha (householder), (3) vānaprastha (forest-dweller/hermit), and (4) saṃnyāsi/yati (ascetic/renunciant). The major smritis all recognize these four stages, but they do not treat them identically.\n\n**Manusmṛti** (unknown-manusmrti-347b76, ch. 6) gives the most systematic āśrama doctrine. At Mn_6.87, it states: 'The celibate student, the householder, the forest-dweller, and the ascetic—these four separate āśramas originate from the householder' (p-59814f). The text insists on sequential, orderly progression (Mn_6.88), and explicitly elevates the householder above all others: 'the householder is declared to be the most excellent, for he supports these other three' (Mn_6.89, p-2acddc), using the simile that all rivers find rest in the ocean as all āśramas find support in the householder (Mn_6.90, p-a6e55e). One must discharge three debts (Vedic study, sons, sacrifice) before legitimately seeking liberation (Mn_6.35–37). Manu also notes differential ritual intensity across āśramas (purification is double for celibate students, triple for forest-dwellers, quadruple for ascetics — Mn_5.137).\n\n**Yājñavalkya Smṛti** (unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6) covers the four āśramas across two chapters: student and householder in ch. 1 (sections 2 and 5), forest-dweller (vānaprasthadharmaprakaraṇam) and ascetic (yatidharmaprakaraṇam) in ch. 3 (sections 3–4). Notably, Yj_3.65 (p-f263eb) qualifies the āśrama system: 'The stage of life is not the cause of dharma; it becomes so only when it is practiced. Therefore, what is harmful to oneself, one should not do to others.' This is a more flexible and internalized stance than Manu's — the external āśrama identity is not itself the source of dharma, but the actual practice of its principles is.\n\n**Viṣṇu Smṛti** (unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8) frames its entire text as declaring 'the eternal laws of the four varṇas along with the practices of the āśramas' (Vi_1.62–63, p-cdc451). Its structural distribution is telling: brahmacāri in ch. 28, householder in chs. 58–93 (dozens of chapters), vānaprastha in chs. 94–95 (brief), and the renunciant (pravrajyāśramī) in ch. 96. Renunciation (Vi_96.1) requires 'having been purified of his passions in the three stages of life' — a sequential prerequisite echoing Manu.\n\n**Parāśara Smṛti** (unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be) positions itself as specifically for the Kali Yuga (Par_1.24), focusing on simplified householder conduct and hospitality duties. It does not develop a systematic four-āśrama doctrine.\n\n**Other smritis** in the corpus (Āṅgirasa, Nārada, Bṛhaspati, Kātyāyana) deal primarily with ritual impurity, śrāddha, and legal/vyavahāra matters; they mention ascetics and householders in scattered rules but do not expound the four-āśrama system.\n\n**Summary of variation**: The four āśramas are universally acknowledged across the corpus, but not treated identically. Manusmriti gives the most elaborate sequential doctrine, explicitly crowning the householder as supreme. Yājñavalkya introduces a notable qualification that the āśrama label alone does not confer dharmic status — practice matters more than stage. Viṣṇu Smṛti shares Manu's sequential logic but reveals different structural priorities by devoting far more space to householder duties. Parāśara Smṛti largely bypasses the āśrama framework, offering Kali-yuga-specific conduct instead.",
